  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Letter of Gratitude to Minister Yuan
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly present this letter. I have received with profound gratitude the special favor of the Grand Commandant, who has graciously elevated me to a higher post. My joy knows no bounds.

    I am but a humble scholar from Hyeonto, possessed of the merest talents—like the smallest insects that nest upon mosquito eyebrows. Yet through early devotion to goodness, I have somehow earned a modest name. Since then, my path as a wanderer has been fraught with sorrow, and lacking patrons of influence, my simple robes have been dyed in indigo while my studies, scarcely begun, have been bent beneath the weight of office.

    Reflecting upon the past year, from the moment I first presented myself at court and took up my undeserving post at the Zheng Station, Minister Yuan has shown me nothing but genuine encouragement and selfless support. Through your recommendation, this rootless tree has found grounding, and these fledgling wings have dared to harbor dreams of soaring among the clouds.

    Now, suddenly, I find myself undeservedly elevated to rank, and I am deeply ashamed of the whispered reproach that I am unfit for such station. Though I embrace service to the realm, how can I content myself merely drawing salary while lacking true merit? Like a quail adorned in a hawk's feathers, I now recognize my presumption. Like a sparrow among cranes, I know well my place and my failure.

    I had prepared a formal petition for your reconsideration. This is why I have not yet come to offer my personal thanks. Now, receiving your generous and gracious words, I am moved beyond measure, and my gratitude overflows all bounds.
  footnotes:
    - Hyeonto (玄菟) refers to an ancient kingdom in the Korean peninsula, here used by the author to humbly identify his origins.
    - The 'insects on mosquito eyebrows' and similar vivid metaphors reflect the author's characteristic self-deprecating style, employing nature imagery to express humility.
    - Minister Yuan (元郞中) held significant influence at court and had been instrumental in the author's advancement.
    - The paired images of the quail in hawk's feathers and the sparrow among cranes are classical expressions of one's sense of unworthiness and misplacement.
